TEXT(beginproblem());


TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 

Let \[p(x) = x^3-x^2+2x-5.\]

$BR
\(p(-3)\) can be computed via synthetic division by
filling in for the letters \(a\) through \(g\) in the table

\[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & -1 & 2 & -5 \\
  & b & d & f \\
a & c & e & g \\
\end{array}
\]

where

$BR
 \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=a\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp( 1));


TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=b\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp( -3));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR  \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=c\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp( -4));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR  \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=d\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(12));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR  \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=e\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(14));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=f\),
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(-42));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR \{ ans_rule(5) \} \(=g\).
$BR
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(-47));


TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
Moreover,
\(p(-3) =\) \{ ans_rule(5) \} and
EOT
ANS(num_cmp(-47));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
\(p(x)\) can be written as
\[p(x) = (x+3)q(x) + r \]
where 
$BR
\(q(x) =\) \{ ans_rule(20) \} is a quadratic polynomial and
EOT
ANS(fun_cmp("x*x-4*x+14", limits=>[[1,2]], vars=>["x"]));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT)); 
$BR
\(r=\)  \{ ans_rule(20) \} is a real number.
EOT


ANS(num_cmp(-47));




SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT')); 
$BR $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD Our matrix becomes

\[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & -1 & 2 & -5 \\
  & -3 & 12 & -42 \\
1 & -4 & 14 & -47 \\
\end{array}
\]

Thus \[p(x) = (x+3)(x^2-4x+14) -47\]
and \(p(-3) = -47\).



EOT




ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
